"><h3 id=3D"degrees-of-freedom-df">Degrees of Freedom (DF)</h3><p>Associate=
d with each sum of squares is a quantity called degrees of freedom (DF). Th=
e degrees of freedom indicate the number of independent pieces of informati=
on used to calculate each sum of squares. For a one factor design with a fa=
ctor at k levels (five lots in our example) and a total of N observations (=
five jars per lot for a total of 25), the degrees of freedom are as follows=
:</p><p><em>Table 5: Determining degrees of freedom</em></p></div><div clas=
s=3D"table-wrapper"><div class=3D"table striped block" data-block-name=3D"t=
able" data-block-status=3D"loaded"><table><thead><tr><th scope=3D"col"></th=
><th scope=3D"col"><p>Degrees of Freedom (DF) Formula</p></th><th scope=3D"=
